TI  - Patient-reported emotional responses and coping mechanisms in cancer recurrence: a systematic review of qualitative evidence
PY  - 2025
T2  - Supportive Care in Cancer
VL  - 33
IS  - 7
C7  - 604
DO  - 10.1007/s00520-025-09643-y
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105008520119&doi=10.1007%2Fs00520-025-09643-y&partnerID=40&md5=916c5314fdea8514e621a085a60bdbdc
AB  - Purpose: This systematic review aimed to synthesize qualitative evidence on the emotional experiences and coping strategies of patients facing cancer recurrence. The study sought to answer: How do patients experience and cope with cancer recurrence, and what factors influence their emotional and coping responses? Methods: A systematic search was conducted across CINAHL, PubMed, ScienceDirect, Embase, and Medline databases for qualitative studies published between January 2013 and December 2023. Eight qualitative and mixed-methods studies met the inclusion criteria. The data were analyzed using thematic synthesis, and the findings were evaluated using the GRADE-CERQual framework. Results: The analysis revealed six primary emotional experiences: shock and disbelief, fear and anxiety, sadness and grief, anger and frustration, isolation and loneliness, and hope and resilience. Patients employed diverse coping strategies, including information seeking, maintaining hope, utilizing social support, engaging in physical activities, using complementary therapies, emotional expression, information avoidance, goal setting, and accessing psychological support. The study also identified various personal and contextual factors that influenced these emotional and coping responses. Conclusion: The findings highlight the complex interplay between emotional experiences and coping strategies in cancer recurrence, providing essential insights for healthcare providers. This understanding is crucial for developing targeted interventions and improving patient-centered care approaches, ultimately enhancing patient outcomes and quality of life. © The Author(s), under exclusive licence to Springer-Verlag GmbH Germany, part of Springer Nature 2025.
