TI  - Dietary and lifestyle adjustments among people who use drugs in opioid substitution treatment and recommendations for program development: A qualitative study
PY  - 2025
T2  - Social Sciences and Humanities Open
VL  - 12
C7  - 102309
DO  - 10.1016/j.ssaho.2025.102309
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105023978908&doi=10.1016%2Fj.ssaho.2025.102309&partnerID=40&md5=2522b18c91ad62dcd4226c875dd48d70
AB  - Opioid Substitution Therapy (OST) is a widely used intervention for treating Opioid Use Disorder (OUD). However, little is known about the dietary habits and physical activity practices of People Who Use Drugs (PWUD) undergoing OST, especially in Lebanon. This qualitative study explores the dietary practices and lifestyle adjustments of PWUD undergoing OST in Lebanon. Semi-structured Key informant interviews (KIIs) were conducted with 11 male participants recruited from three OST clinics. These interviews focused on participants’ experiences with substance use, treatment, diet, physical activity, and perceived barriers to healthy living during recovery. Thematic analysis revealed significant changes in dietary behaviors and physical health, including weight loss during drug use and weight gain during recovery. Psychological factors, including depression and emotional triggers, were linked to poor eating habits and sedentary lifestyles. Participants expressed a need for structured support in nutrition and physical activity, though barriers such as time constraints and lack of motivation hindered engagement. Recommendations are made for piloting tailored interventions, including personalized dietary counseling and flexible physical activity programs, to address the specific needs of this population. These findings highlight the importance of a holistic approach to OST that includes nutritional and physical activity interventions to improve recovery outcomes. © © 2025. Published by Elsevier Ltd.
