TY  - JOUR
AU  - Chiang, B.N.
AU  - Lee, S.S.
AU  - Mu, J.Y.
TI  - Maximal treadmill exercise stress testing in angiographically documented coronary artery disease in Chinese
PY  - 1977
T2  - Chinese Medical Journal (Taipei)
VL  - 24
IS  - 2
SP  - 115
EP  - 126
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-0017665764&partnerID=40&md5=e52a88df16d33245ea5edd80f4187f49
AB  - Maximal treadmill exercise test is a valuable clinical noninvasive method in the detection of suspected coronary artery disease and in estimating the extent and severity of coronary pathology, providing both qualitative and quantitative assessment of coronary artery disease. Maximal treadmill exercise test for Chinese patients suspected of having coronary artery disease has a sensitivity of 86% and specificity of 73%. The low specificity is related to prevalence of hypertensive patients among Chinese population who often exhibit positive ST response upon maximal exercise, yet have normal coronary arteriogram as shown in our previous study. In the present series, 72.7% of all false positive cases were hypertensive. Maximal treadmill exercise test may characterize left, main and triple vessel disease by lower exercise tolerance ≤3 min, downsloping pattern of ST segment depression, marked magnitude of ST depression ≥ 3mm, often occurring during exercise rather than postexercise. False positive maximal treadmill exercise test response is often characterized by higher exercise tolerance ≥6 min, upsloping ST depression of less magnitude ≤2.9 mm and onset of ST depression occurring in postexercise period. ST depression upon maximal exercise is a nonspecific functional expression of imbalance between myocardial oxygen supply and demand. It does not provide anatomical information, and false positive response may occur in various conditions other than coronary artery disease. The limitation of low specificity in this series is obvious. An abnormal ST response does not absolutely predict the presence of coronary artery disease. Conversely, a negative ST response does not rule out this possibility. Thus, the result of an exercise stress test must be interpreted in the entire clinical context, and in appropriately selected cases, the minimal risk of coronary arteriography is justified in order to establish definite anatomical diagnosis.
